1. Introduction to Git and GitHub
1.1 What is Git

Git is a distributed version control system (VCS)

It tracks changes in code/files over time

Created by Linus Torvalds (2005)

1.2 What is GitHub

GitHub is a cloud platform to host Git repositories

Used for:

Collaboration

Code sharing

Version management

1.3 Difference Between Git and GitHub

Git → tool (local system)

GitHub → platform (remote server)

2. Git Architecture
2.1 Three Main Areas

Working Directory

Where you edit files

Staging Area (Index)

Where changes are prepared

Repository (Local Repo)

Where commits are stored

3. Git Installation and Setup
3.1 Install Git

Linux:

sudo apt install git
3.2 Configure Git
git config --global user.name "Your Name"
git config --global user.email "your@email.com"
4. Basic Git Commands
4.1 Initialize Repository
git init
4.2 Check Status
git status
4.3 Add Files
git add file.txt
git add .
4.4 Commit Changes
git commit -m "message"
5. Branching in Git
5.1 What is Branch

A branch is a separate line of development

5.2 Commands
git branch
git branch new-branch
git checkout new-branch
git switch new-branch
5.3 Merge Branch
git merge branch-name
6. Remote Repository (GitHub)
6.1 Add Remote
git remote add origin https://github.com/user/repo.git
6.2 Push Code
git push -u origin main
6.3 Pull Code
git pull origin main
6.4 Clone Repository
git clone https://github.com/user/repo.git
7. Git Workflow
7.1 Basic Workflow

Modify files

git add

git commit

git push

7.2 Collaboration Workflow

Clone repo

Create branch

Make changes

Push branch

Create Pull Request

8. GitHub Concepts
8.1 Repository

Storage space for project

8.2 Fork

Copy of another repository

8.3 Pull Request (PR)

Request to merge changes

8.4 Issues

Track bugs/tasks

9. Git Commands for History
9.1 View Logs
git log
9.2 Short Log
git log --oneline
9.3 Difference
git diff
10. Undoing Changes
10.1 Unstage File
git reset file.txt
10.2 Undo Commit
git reset --soft HEAD~1
10.3 Discard Changes
git checkout -- file.txt
11. Advantages of Git
11.1 Benefits

Distributed system

Fast and efficient

Supports branching

Easy collaboration
